'''Operation Atlantic''' (18–21 July 1944) was a Canadian offensive during the [[Operation Overlord|Battle of Normandy]] in the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The offensive, launched in conjunction with [[Operation Goodwood]] by the Second Army, was part of operations to seize the French city of [[Caen]] and vicinity from German forces. It was initially successful, with gains made on the flanks of the [[Orne River]] near [[Saint-André-sur-Orne]] but an attack by the [[4th Canadian Infantry Brigade|4th]] and [[6th Canadian Infantry Brigade]]s of the [[2nd Canadian Infantry Division]], against strongly defended German positions on [[Verrières Ridge]] to the south was a costly failure.

==Background==
===Operation Overlord===
{{Further|Invasion of Normandy|Operation Overlord}}

The capture of the historic Norman town of [[Caen]], while "ambitious", was the most important [[Normandy Landings|D-Day]] objective assigned to British [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[John Crocker]]'s [[I Corps (United Kingdom)|I Corps]] and its component [[3rd Division (United Kingdom)|British 3rd Infantry Division]], which landed on [[Sword Beach|Sword]] on 6 June 1944.<ref>Williams, p. 24</ref><ref name="Ellis, p. 171">Ellis, p. 171</ref>{{#tag:ref|"The quick capture of that key city Caen and the neighbourhood of Carpiquet was the most ambitious, the most difficult and the most important task of [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[John Crocker|J.T. Crocker]]'s [[I Corps (United Kingdom)|I Corps]]".<ref name="Ellis, p. 171"/> Wilmot states "The objectives given to Crocker's seaborne divisions were decidedly ambitious, since his troops were to land last, on the most exposed beaches, with the farthest to go, against what was potentially the greatest opposition."<ref>Wilmot, p. 273</ref> However [[Miles Dempsey|Miles C. Dempsey]], commanding the [[Second Army (United Kingdom)|British Second Army]], always considered the possibility that the immediate seizure of Caen might fail.<ref>Buckley, p. 23</ref>|group=nb}} Operation Overlord plans called for British Second Army to secure the city and form a line from [[Caumont-l'Éventé]] to the south-east of Caen, thus acquiring ground for airfields and protecting the left flank of the [[First United States Army|U.S. First Army]], under [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]] [[Omar Bradley|Omar N. Bradley]], as it moved on [[Cherbourg]].<ref>Ellis, p. 78</ref> Possession of Caen and its surroundings would give Second Army jumping-off points to attack southwards and capture [[Falaise, Calvados|Falaise]], which would in turn act as a pivot for a swing right to advance on [[Argentan]] and then the [[Touques River]].<ref>Ellis, p. 81</ref> The terrain between Caen and [[Vimont, Calvados|Vimont]] was open, dry and conducive to swift offensive operations. Since the Allied forces greatly outnumbered the Germans in tanks and mobile units, a mobile battle was to their advantage.<ref>Van-Der-Vat, p. 146</ref>

On D-Day the 3rd Division was unable to assault Caen in force and was brought to a halt north of the city.<ref>Wilmot, pp. 284–286</ref> Follow-up attacks failed as German resistance solidified. [[Operation Perch]], a [[pincer attack]] by I and [[XXX Corps (United Kingdom)|XXX Corps]], began on 7 June, with the intention of encircling Caen from the east and west.<ref name="Forty36">Forty, p. 36</ref> I Corps, striking south out of the [[6th Airborne Division (United Kingdom)#D-Day|Orne bridgehead]], was halted by the [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st Panzer Division]] and the attack by XXX Corps bogged down in front of [[Tilly-sur-Seulles]] due to stout resistance by the [[Panzer-Lehr-Division]].<ref name="Forty36"/><ref>Ellis, pp. 247–250</ref> In an effort to force the Panzer-Lehr to withdraw or surrender, and to keep operations fluid, the [[7th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|British 7th Armoured Division]] pushed through a recently created gap in the German front line to capture the town of [[Villers-Bocage, Calvados|Villers-Bocage]].<ref>Ellis, p. 254</ref><ref>Taylor, p. 10</ref> The resulting day-long [[Battle of Villers-Bocage|battle]] saw the vanguard of the British 7th Armoured Division withdraw from the town, but by 17 June Panzer-Lehr had been forced back and XXX Corps had taken Tilly-sur-Seulles.<ref>Forty, p. 97</ref><ref>Taylor, p. 76</ref> Further offensive operations were postponed on 19 June, when a severe storm wracked the [[English Channel]] for three days, delaying the Allied build-up.<ref name="Williams114">Williams, p. 114</ref>

On 26 June the British launched [[Operation Epsom]], an attempt by Lieutenant-General [[Richard O'Connor]]'s [[VIII Corps (United Kingdom)|VIII Corps]] to outflank Caen's defenses by crossing the [[River Odon]] to the west of the city then circling eastward.<ref>Clark, pp. 31–32</ref><ref>Clark, pp. 32–33</ref> The attack was preceded by [[Operation Martlet]], which secured VIII Corps' line of advance by capturing the high ground on their right.<ref name="Clark21">Clark, p. 21</ref> The Germans managed to contain the offensive but were forced to commit all their armor, including two panzer divisions newly arrived in Normandy,<ref>Hart, p. 108</ref><ref>Reynolds (2002), p. 13</ref> which forced them to cancel a planned offensive against British and American positions around Bayeux.<ref>Wilmot, p. 334</ref> Several days later Second Army launched a new offensive, codenamed [[Operation Charnwood]], against Caen.<ref name="Williams131"/> Charnwood incorporated a postponed attack on [[Carpiquet]], originally planned for Epsom as Operation Ottawa but now codenamed [[Operation Windsor]].<ref name="Stacey150">Stacey, p. 150</ref><ref name="Jackson60">Jackson, p. 60</ref> In a frontal assault on 8–9 July the northern half of the city was captured.<ref name="Williams131">Williams, p. 131</ref> German forces still held part of the city on the southern side of the Orne river, including the Colombelles steel works, a vantage point for artillery observers.<ref name="Stacey150">Stacey, p. 150</ref>

==Prelude==
===Plan===
[[File:AtlanticGoodwood Battle plan.jpg|thumb|Postwar map shows the planned attack for Operations Atlantic and Goodwood. It also shows where Second Army had confirmed the locations of several German divisions as well as where they believed others where located.]]
On 10 July General [[Bernard Montgomery]], commander of all Allied ground forces in Normandy, held a meeting with Lieutenant-Generals [[Miles Dempsey]] and [[Omar Bradley]], respectively the commanders of [[Second Army (United Kingdom)|British Second Army]] and the [[First United States Army|United States First Army]], at his headquarters to discuss the next attacks to be launched by [[21st Army Group]]<ref name=Trew49>Trew, p. 49</ref> following the conclusion of Operation Charnwood and the failure of the First Army's initial breakout offensive.<ref>Wilmot, p. 351</ref> Montgomery approved [[Operation Cobra]],<ref>Williams, p. 175</ref> a major break out attempt to be launched by the First Army on 18 July, and ordered Dempsey to "go on hitting: drawing the German strength, especially the armour, onto yourself - so as to ease the way for Brad[ley]".<ref name="Trew49"/>

Detailed planning for Operation Goodwood began on Friday 14 July.<ref>Jackson, p. 79</ref> On 15 July Montgomery issued a written order to Dempsey scaling back the operation. These new orders changed the operation from a "deep break-out to a limited attack".<ref name="Trew66">Trew, p. 66</ref> The intention of the operation was now "to engage the German armour in battle and "write it down" to such an extent that it is of no further value to the Germans", and to improve the Second Army's position.<ref>Ellis, pp. 330–331</ref> The orders stated that "a victory on the eastern flank will help us to gain what we want on the western flank" but warned that operations must not endanger Second Army's position, as it was a "firm bastion" that was needed for the success of American operations.<ref name="Ellis331">Ellis, p. 331</ref> It was stressed that II Canadian Corps' objectives were now vital, and only following their completion would VIII Corps be free to " "crack about" as the situation demands".<ref name="Ellis331"/>

Lt. Gen. [[Guy Simonds]]' [[II Canadian Corps]] would launch an attack, codenamed Operation Atlantic, on the western flank of VIII Corps to liberate Colombelles and the remaining portion of Caen south of the Orne river.<ref>Stacey, p. 169</ref> Following the capture of these areas, the Corps was to be prepared to capture [[Verrières, Orne|Verrières]] Ridge.<ref>Stacey, pp. 170–171</ref> The Atlantic–Goodwood operation was slated to commence on 18 July, two days before the planned start of Operation Cobra.<ref name="Williams161">Williams, p. 161</ref>

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-721-0353-27A, Collombelles, Soldaten auf Feld vor Fabrik.jpg|thumb|A German patrol moves towards the Colombelles factory area.]]
Preparations for ''Atlantic'' were delegated to General Simonds, in his first action as the commander of II Canadian Corps.<ref name=bercuson222>Bercuson, p. 222</ref> He planned the operation as a two-pronged assault, relying on the [[2nd Canadian Infantry Division|2nd]] and [[3rd Canadian Infantry Division]]s to capture Vaucelles, Colombelles, and the opposite banks of the Orne River.<ref name=bercuson222/> On the morning of 18 July, Gen. [[Rod Keller]]'s 3rd Division would cross the Orne near Colombelles, and then proceed south towards Route Nationale 158.<ref name=bercuson222/> The 3rd Division would then move to capture Cormelles.<ref name=roy68>Roy, p. 68</ref> The 2nd Division, under the command of Gen. [[Charles Foulkes (Canadian Army general)|Charles Foulkes]], would attack from Caen to the south-east, crossing the Orne to capture the outskirts of Vaucelles. They would then use Cormelles as a jumping-off point for an attack on the high ground near Verrières Ridge three miles to the south.

==Battle==
On the morning of 18 July, with heavy air support, advance elements of the 3rd Canadian Infantry Division were able to capture Colombelles and Faubourg-de-Vaucelles, a series of industrial suburbs just south of Caen along the Orne River. By mid-afternoon, two companies of the [[Black Watch (Royal Highland Regiment) of Canada|Black Watch]] had crossed the Orne River, with 'A' Company taking fewer than twenty casualties.<ref>''Copp, The Approach to Verrières Ridge''</ref> Additional Battalions from 5th Brigade managed to push southward to Saint-André-sur-Orne.<ref name="ReferenceA">''Copp, Approach to Verrières Ridge''</ref> With the east bank of the Orne River secured, the 4th and 6th Canadian Infantry Brigades moved into position for the assault on Verrières Ridge.<ref>''Jarymowycz'', Pg. 3</ref>

The German High Command ([[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|OKW]]) had not missed the strategic importance of the ridge. Though nowhere more than {{convert|90|ft|m|abbr=on}} high, it dominated the Caen–Falaise road, blocking Allied forces from breaking out into the open country south of Caen. The [[1st SS Panzer Corps]] ([[Sepp Dietrich]]) and parts of the [[1st SS Division Leibstandarte SS Adolf Hitler]], defended the area, amply provided with artillery, ''[[nebelwerfer]]'' and tanks.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

Units of the Queen's Own Cameron Highlanders of Canada, supporting the [[South Saskatchewan Regiment]] of the 2nd Division, were able to secure a position in St. André-sur-Orne in the early hours of 20 July but were soon pinned down by German infantry and tanks.<ref>Bercuson, p. 220</ref> A simultaneous direct attack up the slopes of Verrières Ridge by the South Sakatchewans fell apart as heavy rain prevented air support and turned the ground to muck, making it difficult for tanks to maneuver. Counterattacks by two Panzer divisions forced the South Saskatchewans back past their start line and crashed into their supporting battalion, the [[The Essex Scottish Regiment|Essex Scottish]],<ref name="ReferenceB">Zuehlke, Pg. 166</ref> who lost over 300 men as they struggled to hold back the 1th SS Panzer Division. Meanwhile, to the east, the remainder of I SS Panzer Corps fought the largest armored battle of the campaign, with British forces involved in Operation Goodwood.<ref>Bercuson, p. 223</ref> By the end of the day, the South Saskatchewan Regiment had taken 282 casualties and the ridge was still in enemy hands.

Simonds remained determined to take the ridge. He sent in two battalions, the Black Watch and the Calgary Highlanders, to stabilize the situation, and minor counterattacks by both, on 21 July, managed to contain Dietrich's armored formations. By the time the operation was called off, Canadian forces held several footholds on the ridge, including a now secure position on Point 67. Four German divisions still held the ridge. In all, the actions around Verrières Ridge during Operation Atlantic accounted for over 1,300 Allied casualties.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>

==Aftermath==
===Analysis===
Caen south of the Orne was captured, but the failure to seize Verrières Ridge led Montgomery to issue orders on 22 July for another offensive, this time to be a "holding attack", within a few days, in conjunction with Operation Cobra.<ref>''Copp, Approach to Verrières Ridge p.</ref> As a result, Lieutenant-General Guy Simonds formulated the plans for [[Operation Spring]]. The contemporaneous [[Battle of Verrières Ridge]] claimed over 2,600 Canadian casualties by the end of 26 July.<ref name="Zuehlke, Pg. 166"/>

===Casualties===
The Canadian Official Historian, C. P. Stacey, gave Canadian casualties in all services of 1,965 men, 441 of whom were killed or died of wounds.<ref name="Stacey, p. 176">Stacey, p. 176</ref> Copp recorded from {{nowrap|1,349–1,965 Canadian}} casualties in Operation Atlantic,  the majority in the 4th and 6th Canadian Infantry Brigades.<ref name="Zuehlke, Pg. 166">''Zuehlke'', Pg. 166</ref><ref name="Stacey, p. 176"/><ref>Copp, p. 5</ref>

